Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9 per cent of the school population and obesity affects 5 per cent.
Obese children come mostly from families with a lifestyle that is unhealthy, according to current research.
It again demonstrates the importance of the environment where it grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as reference.
At the table, obsessing children feed, for example, on sausages at least twice as often as children from normal weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of obese people had eaten fries the day before the test, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence".
In families of overweight children there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and nearly 900 basic education children from all over the Czech Republic participated in the survey.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a chance", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from 4th to 8th grade.
A proper diet and plenty of exercise in the family are determining factors, which make the number of overweight and even obese children significantly decrease.
"Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals a day according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet," picks up one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast but with lunch for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, the details, which also count, are also important, such as having a fixed hour for breakfast as a family.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 per cent of families of schoolchildren have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each one has breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households nothing is eaten.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that families of obese children are much more often consumed by unhealthy potato chips.
Almost all - regardless of weight - drink daily soft drinks (70%).
As a rule, more than 40 per cent of the children surveyed do sports, but among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15 per cent.
Make up your diet
The next phase of the study made it possible for the chosen children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far from ideal."
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
"The popularity of soft drinks is particularly alarming," the study's final report warns.
As the main food, the pasta is taken from the palm and followed closely by the poultry meat.
Practically, children always reject the legume and taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of the participants in the study, who completed the questionnaire after finishing the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence", in many cases there was a significant change in favor of the principles of a healthy diet", it is pointed out in the results of the study.
Attention is drawn, for example, to sweet refreshments, where many children would begin to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also more frequently choose poultry meat and fish for the main meal in the questionnaire and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
