Brand story:
Innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were to look for a term that defined IBM's strategy with great precision, the most approximate would be "long term".
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet a hundred years have passed since its foundation.
The basis of this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, visionary Thomas J. Watson.
He has already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his label, around which the life of the giant future will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully raised corporate culture.
"For us, IBM implies long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
