History of IBM: from the cheese cutter to space flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York 100 years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was already adopted in 1924 - originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The basis that gave rise to the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He owned inventions such as the famous "log-in clock", which allows controlling the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his supervisory council.
Flint signed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him manage the company.
The new leader overshadowed the founder of IBM ( Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business equipment, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson ran the company, turnover doubled by $9 million and began the company's great expansion across continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that after almost forty years occupying the boss's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "peses", which established the computer standard of that time, arrived on the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer complete advice and services of high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet."
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not improved, for example in terms of transport and city administration.
For the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch office in Czechoslovakia then, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team working with voice recognition.
