How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at that time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was severely restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but one had to stand in line with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The Czechs' way of travel has suffered a genuine revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that Croatia, the currently favorite destination, could not travel freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed for travel to neighbouring Western European States, resulting in an enormous wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was the taking with them the food (conservatives, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and so did average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare travel using charter connections, which led to an incredible drop in travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs were already travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries depart every year. This winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15 thousand Czech kroner per head on overseas trips, including expenses on the stay site.
