The intense and generous new book by Peter Englund, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An intimate story about World War I, "begins with a long personae dramatis of the kind that can make one drop his soul at his feet.
Here are some action tips: Gently rip this page off and turn it into your brand pages.
You will come to know these people very well in the novelist narrative of Mr. Englund, and this personae dramatis will function as his GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men and women, he is confused and helpless in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
What he has written here is an unusual book, which he rightly describes as "an anti-history work".
It contains some notable names, important treatises or famous battles; there are virtually no ambassadors, elegant journalists or discussions about tactics or material.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as "a book about how it happened." It's about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"The beauty and pain of battle "combines the wartime experiences of about 20 ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and administrative.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Some will become prisoners of war, or lose their limbs, go mad, or die.
Their lives flash here like votive candles lit in a church; some new ones add to the mix while others go out.
Mr. Englund's book is a deviation from standard history books.
It is also a correction to the notion that World War I was only the disastrous trench war on the western front.
"The beauty and pain of battle" moves expertly through other war theatres: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book fall on hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tse-tse flies are an intractable problem.
This is a moving book, almost from the beginning.
The war floods the lives of these people as a natural catastrophe, a Hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When the artillery fire is heard in the distance, and you are a woman who is at home with your children, do you stay or run?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one understands what is going on, not even why this war has to be fought.
"Factlessness," observes Mr. Englund, "has been filled with conjectures, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
