7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview Shown In A Theatre This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs, on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius from technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in an interview with Jobs recently rediscovered that has been dusted as a preview of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a designer, dreamer and self-recognised hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a junkie of flowcharts - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for over an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensely on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transportation.
It was only after Jobs died that a complete copy of VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly reissued archive material is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute missing interview that arrives at Landmark cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose their technology philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when the perfectionism of Jobs comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster towards the most important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It is one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Job's career, but there is something crude and inspiring in the Jobs that we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they invariably give you are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs brings your efforts to the detail to simplify Apple's accounting.
Disconcerted by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made at the eye of a good cook, and then adjusted with a "variable" - developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the Pope's Joke:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long distance calls for free.
It has been written extensively about the device, but the euphoria of Jobs here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and screaming through the pay phone and returning a minute later to the pay phone next door," says Jobs with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing - it was an amazing lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two burst out in laughter just before the Pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling on the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute telephone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
On improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of base plates, a client asked him if he could assemble the entire team.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while on Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
