Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's revival, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble into their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, so what?"
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make electrons do, glass makes them, robots make them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end everything is reduced to taste - it is reduced to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been embarrassed about stealing big ideas.
What made the Macintosh big in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who by chance were the best computer scientists in the world.
