How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone affirming to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with violations of campaign funding related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been instances in which teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Surely, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a serious knowledge branch based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been refuted.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush, or get restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or expose.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years canvassing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more lies "oriented toward others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie to their partners less often than people who are not married (but the lies they often say tend to be "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do I know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "create a baseline."
It helps to provide benchmarks for later measurement of changes.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
You'd better know if someone normally beats his foot all the time to avoid making unfair accusations when he sees his feet pounding in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavior groups as alarm signals, not as evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean towards an exit, change their posture significantly, or display a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Questioners often falsely show that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up and used the past time as he claimed his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
