Valid "analogue blackout" cut in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes between the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue blackout" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes necessary to invalidate it did not meet.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to complete the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed because it did not reach a qualified majority of eight votes in order for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the reservation of law.
Only Zaldivar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without going into the discussion of the project, also in charge of the minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to be prepared.
"I don't think that if I did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, who has a constitutional mandate, the governing body of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, resulting in better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitization, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic governance of the State, includes a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and he has done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, which in some way invades the sphere of competence of Congress, since compliance with the laws issued by the Legislature is being provided in the administrative sphere, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of this year's electoral process in Michoacan, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacan (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local norms with federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or Electoral Justice Act, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the current electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted their publication within the time limits provided for in the Law on the Official State Newspaper, on the grounds that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local legislative branch and called the state president's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal," since he has no right to "sanction or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total recounts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may occur in cases where: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of counting and counting in the file of the box or is not held by the president of the box; or, where there are errors or obvious alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all polling stations may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate presumed to have won the election in question and the candidate who has obtained the second place in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the party representative and/or coalition who ran for the second of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the vote may also be made if, at the end of the ordinary count, it is established that the difference between the candidate presumed to have won and the candidate located in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case electoral packages that have been partially counted will be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
