Quinteto included the country in his two-decade-long celebration tour
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of their best concerts next Sunday, at the National Stadium.
It has been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band assures that for them, too, the dream of playing in the country will become a reality.
This was assured by bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively to Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is on the South American wing of its two decades of work celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make its only stopover in Central America.
On that day they will be presented at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., together with the angeline band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, whose full transcript is on The Nation on the Internet.
For their Costa Rican followers, it is a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've been to Costa Rica only once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we're gonna be able to stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to take our music there.
I ask because there is some kind of devotion to the band, fans live intensely the previous days.
What do they tell their most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for having waited so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played over the past 21 years have happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in São Paulo and we hope that made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we're very anxious to play there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to surf to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they've been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never touched there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this about?
I think it's partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we have not played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we could have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting to people.
With this tour, they're celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything they've accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined we'd be in a big rock band and doing it for more than 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world that we always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of the grunge?
It's always been an honor to be part of that big band.
We are very close to the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a city band emerges, but it is much more strange when five or ten bands leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on his tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them still and we're honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It is also very strange that a band like yours should stay together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
First, I think we are all fortunate to be still alive and, second, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened that give everyone freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance sheet?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure not to be too much touring because it is easy to fall into that game of the great crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you that you must respect the music and what brought it, without being infatuated by being famous and being a rock star, something none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were many frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very close friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or I see a picture I think of the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know your work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose it for opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with various proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are eager to see what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing he can think of.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There's so many of them.
Among the first ones I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about bassists that I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunge relevant even though it is no longer a fashion?
I think all of us always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about her, she reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time, and, if there's relevance now, I think it's a wonderful thing because it's music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had darker content and has now become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed touched them, I cried when I heard them and they're deep dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a relative or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, they certainly represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
Peru:
Fujimori is admitted again for medical examinations
Former president Alberto Fujimori was admitted Tuesday to a public hospital to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, serving a sentence of 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including a cancer in the language for which he has been operated four times and which is kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told TV channel N that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times from cancer to the tongue, he has a weight loss of 18 kilos, which has been joined by other pathologies such as severe erosive gastritis, the cyst of the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been detained since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the Police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the first years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican pair, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the Uruguayan community resident in Mexico, according to the agenda circulated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "proprietary for the exchange of information on all political issues between the two nations," according to the South American presidency on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the French incident that arose when French president Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay's rejection and the call for consultation of its ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group composed of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has in force with the South American country, since January of this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that did not implement all international standards of tax cooperation.
In the commercial sphere, Mexico and Uruguay have in force since 2004 a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The bigoted plumber passes the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought, untiringly, for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but he has never done so in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which comes this month to stores around the world, has been designed from the beginning to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which allows you to play in three dimensions without using glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy without glasses should work," said Nintendo's specialist press officer in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally intended for that support" , as so far successes such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesperson has argued that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Alvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once overcome, the most experts will be able to give a "second round" to the levels of the game, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions in order to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This incursion of Super Mario in the three dimensions also implies the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that did not occur since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo winks the fans of the saga and repeats the formula of the success of the previous deliveries, consisting in that the plumber of the mustache will have to travel platforms mined of dangers in order to release Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom supports Portillo's extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced this Tuesday that he processed the extradition of former governor Alfonso Portillo to respond in the United States for the conspiracy to launder $70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the country of the North that Portillo to judge him there.
At a press conference, Colom stated that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the executive, bearing in mind that a sentencing court had already ordered extradition.
He claimed that during his term of office he "did not put his hands" in court decisions and processed all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom has done is an executive procedure after all the judicial and constitutional bodies have been exhausted in order to prosecute the ex-mandatario from 2000 to 2004.
According to decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala has been resolved and his human rights guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for the embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defence when he was president, which was the process that preceded extradition, but the Public Prosecutor's Office appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk
The entity was born to avoid the fall in the marginality of untrained children
The balance sheet of the first 25 years of life of the social support entity Trinijove is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have been helped to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter of a century.
In addition to this, there are a hundred long jobs currently available for this social group.
The anniversary served yesterday to take stock of an event held in the old Fabra i Coats factory complex attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the Trinitat Vella neighborhood in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, no work, with problems of dogradiction or in a position to fall into marginality.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu concentrated a large number of heads of entities and institutions that have collaborated with the association in these 25 years.
The varied political representation, in full electoral time, showed the unitary nature of the work carried out by Trinijove.
Together with the President of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the former socialist education consultant Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and current ecosocialist councilman Ricard Gomà attended the event.
The current conseller of Benestar Social i Família, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the director general of the social work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also attended the grand hall of La Fabra i Coats.
But he said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is also, but added that the work done so far "is a good base".
The president gave Trinijove as an example of how to fight bad circumstances and give hope to people in difficulty.
"The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does," he said.
Evicted an squatter farm where they made macro-fests
The invaders had taken possession of 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51
The 12 occupants left the farm yesterday noon without offering resistance
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare experienced by the neighbors of 51 Balmes Street has come to an end.
Twelve people left yesterday's noon voluntarily the property they occupied illegally, and where they organized macro-fests that despaired the neighborhood, by court order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation ended, the door lock was changed to prevent a recurrence of the situation.
"From now on there will be an access control," said the administrator.
The squatters, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building - the rest are inhabited - took away the entire electrical installation and part of the water, as well as painting the walls and leaving waste of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of the mass parties, which lasted for up to two days and made the tenants desperate.
Next to the building there is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that since the building was occupied the business has gone down 80%.
The owner of the discotheque points out that the invaders of the estate made him unfair competition, since they sold the drinks at three euros, while in the discotheque they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the leisure place had had to respond to neighborhood complaints of noise, while, according to him, the inconveniences were not caused by the clients of the discotheque, but by the inhabitants of the squat house and, above all, by those attending the parties that were organized there, which had increased their frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to the angry neighbors of the area.
The head of the discotheque explained that the inconveniences were so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and nine months ago she "forgave" her rent.
The Urban Guard also confirmed that over the past few weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal PP group in the town hall, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had last week called for "immediately unlodging the building to end the problems of coexistence and civicism that produce the neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area".
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the occupied building, but over the last few months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and almost all the floors, and that in some there have even been robberies.
In this sense he added that, "it is necessary to end the impunity and be forceful against the incivism that has been generated in the farm."
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 3.30 p.m., the police proceeded to 35 Mont-ral Street, after receiving a call from a neighbour who had observed that four persons were accessing the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond polemics on fees
The municipal contest on the 16 gates reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the already extinct Metropolitan Corporation of Barcelona (CMB), this administration printed some pasquines of promotion of Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with the New York Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was again placed, in the imaginary of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented on the north-south axis but above (mountain) -below (sea).
Collserola's rating as a natural park results in this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
In these were until, in September, the city council convened a megacompetition composed of 16 contests for so many other access doors to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone pretends to put doors in the field.
The question comes out alone: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it supposes of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all Barcelona architects.
It is almost a recurring subject to be touched upon when two members of this former caste of elect are recognized in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects think, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coast front "it is necessary" to debate about "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, that of green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is possible to start from the base that the most extensive park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things for its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect for whom the title of "Collaserola gates" contains a "lexical trap": they should not be thought of "as the accesses to a park, but the delimitation of areas where action is needed".
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, qualifies the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from how "uncertain it is today to project the public space" after the experience lived in the 80's and had in the area of the Forum "his swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where one can build.
"To limit something is to fix the next step," that is, its overstep.
"It is necessary to think of new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the Metropolitan General Plan (GMP)] can give rise to real disasters."
More close to the question, Mòdol believes that, simplifying, the valley slope of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, no", by a purely topographical question.
Mòdol remembers that there is already a work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "should not fall into a broken sack", although he appreciates the opportunity that the council offers to his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe conduct that allows the architects to enter into the debate, but "doubts" about whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all right", he points out) that they have had to create: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives title to this piece is complex, because in the bases of the contest lacks a global vision of Collserola: "16 transversal contests have been convened -he says- in the sense mountain-sea, but there is no longitudinal reading, that sees and understands the area as a whole".
This means, at least where appropriate, that he has chosen to participate in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors can collide in program and definition with that of the architect next door.
In his view, however, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Dalt Round should provide, in its entirety, for an area of equipment that would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonah Larrazábal and will go free
After 72 days of taking root, the legal representative of Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey for the process that followed him for alleged blackmail
After 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonah Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red granted him the pardon before the Second District Criminal Court, which continues a process of blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on Casino Royale, Casino Red owner Sergio Gil García made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonah allegedly demanded payment of an economic fee so that the regional council would allow the clandestine operation of the gambling house.
Following the public complaint, the State Attorney's Office opened criminal proceedings against the brother of the PAN mayor and on 2 September he was arrested and held for 30 days.
After four hours before the Public Prosecutor's Office Agent 3 in Patrimonial Crimes, he was transferred to the House of Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
He remained there for 49 days following the issuance of a second arrest warrant after the Public Prosecutor's Office officer dismissed the crimes of bribery and organized crime.
On 19 October, he was transferred to Cadereyta prison allegedly for blackmailing the owners of Casino Red with 1.5 million pesos; however, he remained only for a few hours in the medium-security prison because there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was ordered to be arrested by the clerk of the Second District Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that nearly two months after investigations sufficient evidence was checked to determine Jonah's guilt, such as the collection of 1.5 million pesos from the representatives of the gambling house in exchange for allowing it to be operated.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Victor Aldo García Gómez, went before the judge José Luis Pecina to ask for forgiveness for the brother of the royal mayor; so in the next few hours he could recover his freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the public prosecutor attached to the court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and which of the members of the gambling house was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
On the basis of the 197/2011 file, the legal pardon is granted to Jonah Larrazábal and henceforth no complaint may be filed concerning the proceedings that followed him; in addition to that he will not be required to make reparation for harm or punishment.
After the hearing with the legal representative of the gambling house, at about 15:50 Larrazabal Breton was ordered immediately to be released.
The court clerk, Jorge Yánez, moved to the prison of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonah that he has been legally forgiven and his file will be filed.
He will also notify you of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, lost his life, and seven other people
The Ministry of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the terrain, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so he had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that research done in the impact area did not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In a search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
"The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees inclination.
At the moment, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results before possible; however, the research can last several months, it could even reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff operated in cruise speed and that this happened in an ascending soft terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, SCT headline Pérez Jácome listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out under the visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
Reports at the AICM placed appropriate conditions for take-off, as the aircraft progressed towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, layers of cloudiness were present at low altitude.
Selected paths:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew has sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the latest radar aircraft record match, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and side path.
The pattern of the aircraft's debris dispersal suggests that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the disaster, no evidence remains to be revealed in the ship's remains of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the field.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above the average sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was presumably broken down along this route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After the thorough search in a larger area than the cordoned site, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, which reinforces the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security leads research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetic protocol of obesity in childhood and adolescence', which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research, the population is invited to participate, whether or not they are entitled, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He highlighted that the protocol began in the Quauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of West Mexico) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico Oriente).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
When World Diabetes Day was celebrated on 14 November, he said that the goal was to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and inherited family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure intake, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic levels are applied to all participants (genes associated with childhood obesity are sought).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic rise,' noted the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the integral evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the television and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (sizes, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt of UNAM would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a better-performing mixture, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, the potholes could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated altogether.
In his lecture A technological opinion of potholes, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called Maltese, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If they were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, it abounded, a final layer called a rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the proper thickness and the material from which it is made should be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil moistens, the water spreads inside the folder and it is difficult to come out, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only after the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and allow to repair the potholes with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
