In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they wish to die and make arrangements to that effect.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Penal Code so that assisted suicide and euthanasia are permitted, when the patient is considering this option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death."
With medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Canadian Society.
And, despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Québec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report had reached conclusions that did not coincide with the position of the federal Government, which had already stated that it did not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians Favoring Euthanasia
Let us remember that 85 per cent of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia, as they believe it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people are less valuable.
Regarding persons who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that no prosecution should be initiated against them.
In relation to the maintenance or interruption of patient care, the situation is not so clear, according to the authors of the report.
In addition, among its recommendations, it suggests that it should be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The committee of experts also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses end-of-life care without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in health institutions in Canada, the committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered euthanasia and subjected to the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations regarding the findings of the Royal Canadian Society experts' report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of experts who sign the report as "extreme", not least because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill people.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and over 18 years old can ask for help to commit suicide," says Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also stresses that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she described as "manifest in favor of euthanasia."
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Canadian Society, questions especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
