Introduction of a budgetary "gold rule" in the Constitution
On Tuesday, the government of the great Social-Democratic/Christian coalition in power in Austria decided to include in the Constitution a "golden rule" of the budget to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible degradation of Austria's sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced at a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an additional €3 billion in interest each year," said the Vice-Chancellor of Christian Democrat Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to the euro area member countries on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, by the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in an Act with equivalent value.
The measure adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural government deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, as of 2017, the federal state structural government deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
