The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into operation.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first has 1,224 km connecting the St Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, that is, sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge play presents the airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land flow by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to shut off access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us," François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the gas pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom's directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
In order to build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream society.
It was also necessary to strengthen measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project renounced it, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish itself permanently at sea off its coast.
"In case of a breakdown, we'll stop the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller says.
In the event of leakage, gas from the gas pipeline shall therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have foreseen joints that, according to the forecasts, they will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the gas pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by means of a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The flow of gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented the company, for a period of 25 years renewable, the entire gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," Jens Müller says.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been carried out by 30 per cent with the contribution of shareholders and 70 per cent through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy pine-planted coast.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a bookmark.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch to the market a notebook of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, at that time a consultant of the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This kind of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Away has remained the confidential production of the early years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts business people as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with Moleskine's development: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand encompasses a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years has been considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be mentioned that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not completed their baccalaureate and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that "constitute the crux of the problem", says Christian Grapin, General Manager of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of people advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité pointed out that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual deficiencies".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are very far from the target of hiring 6% disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of...1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created a great deal of pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of enterprises with 100 to 199 workers.
